    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "The only way to avoid it is to run `gcmode=archive`, then geth flushes to disk after every block. In normal mode, geth maintains \"as much as possible\" [1] in memory, and does pruning of the stuff before it goes to disk. \r\n\r\n[1]: \"as much as possible\" is not not really true; we flush after about 2 hours of processing time. If a block takes 200ms to process, that comes to about 10K blocks. The idea is that the max time you may have to reprocess blocks after a crash is ~2 hours.\r\n\r\nSo geth is saving to disk, but anything saved to disk cannot be ever pruned. It's a tradeoff.  ",
